    "description": "A man's ceremonial skirt which alternates two panels of red and brown and two of tan and brown, sewn together to form one long panel. All panels have interlacing patterns created through clamped resist dyeing.",
    "justification": null,
    "gallery_text": "Most men\u2019s raffia dance skirts from the Congo are decorated with appliqu\u00e9 and embroidery. The Nogongo and Ngeende, however, are masterful dyers, and often incorporated resist-dye techniques in their skirts. Hungarian anthropologist Emil Torday described the technique in his account of his stay among the Ngongo in 1907 \u2013 1910. This skirt is made by a technique known as stick-clamp-resist. Small flat sticks are stitched to folded squares of cloth that have been dyed red by means of a tannic substance. They are then treated with an iron-rich substance, usually mud, which causes the tannins to turn a rich purplish black. The controlled, angular designs that are revealed when the sticks are removed resemble the geometric motifs seen on embroideries, but the symmetry inherent in the technique sets these designs apart.",
